pr_review_comment_body:
I think I've solved it once and for all!  In `conftest.py` you can define these two key methods

```py
def pytest_runtest_setup(item):
def pytest_runtest_teardown(item, nextitem):
```

With some additional class level attribute saving and extra machinery it appears to all be working as expected.  It got pretty ugly, so I'm going to clean that up tomorrow and then push ;)

> > Again, when initially writing reactive charms, I thought that states were associated with interface objects

> Flags (states) were never associated with interface objects. They were associated with conversations previously and units in the future. I think the idea of saying "a flag can have data associated with it" which in the case of interface flags would be a list of units (well, relation ID / unit pairs).

@johnsca It's possible I'm not expressing it clearly.  **It wasn't _obvious_ that states are associated with units.**  If it appears in the documentation then I missed it, and the way I discovered it was by a deep dive, digging through the code, when something didn't work the way I expected.  It's not _obvious_ because non-interface states _don't work the same way_ and are the _first_ things introduced in the documentation.  Yet they have an identical API.

@JordonPhillips What's the rationale for this?

This is unrelated to your change which should just be decoding to unicode for config errors.

If this is because of some other bug let's address that as a separate PR with a separate set of tests.  I really just want to address the actual customer pain here which is masking errors due to not properly decoding issues.   This change is not directly related to that.

> `echo "my_password" |` 

@mide that is what I'd like to avoid. To expert users, I expect that reading from stdin is a consolidated concept, as is password leaks to shell history. I'd like to avoid a sample command that's a sort of "shooting yourself in the foot" for newcomers or people not so fond on avoiding common pitfalls when using the shell.

Anyway I'm ok whit that solution as is surely clear and explicit, if someone else approves.

